                                                                                       Thursday, April 10, 2025
                                                                                       Brandal, Vestlandet, Norway
======================================================================================================================================================

LOCAL MAN RESCUES CHILD FROM BURNING BUILDING

Brandal – A dramatic rescue unfolded late Tuesday evening when a fire swept through an apartment complex in the Nyjord neighborhood.

Mr. Leif Solheim, a local carpenter aged 29, entered the burning structure without hesitation after hearing cries from within. 
Inside, he discovered young Elise Johansen, age six, trapped beneath debris in a rear bedroom on the third floor.

Despite rapidly worsening conditions and collapsing supports, Mr. Solheim carried the child to safety moments before the roof gave way. 
Both Mr. Solheim and Miss Johansen were treated for smoke inhalation and are expected to make full recoveries.

Fire officials hailed Mr. Solheim’s actions as an act of bravery, with Fire Chief Oddvar Hagen stating, “Without question, his courage 
saved a life.” The mayor’s office has confirmed that Mr. Solheim will be honored at next week’s council meeting.

Neighbors gathered outside the charred remains of the building expressed admiration and gratitude. “He did what few would dare,” said 
Mrs. Ingrid Larsen, who witnessed the event. “He is a credit to our town.”

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

THE RICHARDS FAMILY RETURNS FOR SPRING SEASON

Brandal – The Richards family, familiar to many for their longstanding residence in Brandal and important for the former copper trade, 
has returned to town following an extended absence abroad.

The family will be spending the spring and summer months at their manor house on Slitøya.

In a brief statement, Mrs. Ellen Richards expressed joy at their return. “It is a pleasure to once again walk the familiar roads and 
greet our neighbors.”

A community brunch hosted by the family is scheduled for Sunday, weather permitting.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

SHEEP REPORTED MISSING ON SLITØYA

Slitøya – Concern has arisen among local agricultural circles following reports of a missing flock of sheep from the island pastures 
of Slitøya.

Mr. Henrik Mjelva, a farmer with holdings along the northern ridge of the island, noticed the absence late Monday afternoon during 
routine checks. Approximately 23 sheep are unaccounted for.

Authorities are investigating possible causes, including fencing failures and recent foot traffic in the area. Locals are advised to 
remain alert and report any sightings to the sheriff’s office or Brandal Agricultural Services.

