    its unique architecture and the family’s grip on the metal trade.

    At the height of the copper boom in the mid-1800s, the Richards family employed nearly one-third of Brandal’s population. Schools,
    hospitals, and even the clocktower in Market Square bore plaques in their name. They were hailed as both generous benefactors and
    astute businessmen.

